[[File:Copper(II)-acetate-3D-balls.png|thumb|The Chinese lantern structure adopted by copper(II) acetate dihydrate]] In chemistry, the '''Chinese lantern structure''' is a [[coordination complex]] where two [[metal]] atoms are bridged by four [[Denticity|bidentate]] [[ligand]]s. An example is [[copper(II) acetate]] dihydrate. The name reflects a resemblance between [[ball-and-stick model]]s of the structure and a Chinese [[paper lantern]].
