An '''interferometric gravitational wave detector''' is a [[gravitational wave detector]] that uses [[laser]] [[interferometry]] to detect the influence of [[gravitational wave]]s on light that is moving back and forth between test [[mass]]es.
==Locations== Interferometric gravitational wave detectors include *[[GEO600]] near [[Sarstedt]], Germany, *[[LIGO]] (Laser Interferometer Gravitational-Wave Observatory) in the United States, in [[Hanford Site|Hanford]], Washington, laser beam arms totalling 5 miles, and a 2.5 x 2.5 mile facility in [[Livingston, Louisiana]], 30 miles east of Baton Rouge.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p032v402 A New Ear on the Universe] BBC World Service, 26 September 2015</ref> *[[Virgo interferometer]], near Pisa, Italy.
